  "text": "Based on these findings, we hypothesize that insoluble particles that remain in the ICG solution attached to the iris surface or to the anterior chamber angle during anterior capsular staining without being completely washed off can cause inflammation. Thus, if the formation of insoluble ICG particles can be minimized, inflammation caused by residual ICG particles could be reduced. The dissolution time, solution concentration, and solvent type all contribute to the formation of insoluble ICG particles. Generally, a mixed solution of distilled water and BSS is used to prepare ICG dye solution. Nishimura et al. [CITATION_1] reported that insoluble ICG particles could form when BSS was used to prepare the ICG dye solution.",
